04436nam a22005775i 9780520920361DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19941994cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209203617 a10.1525/97805209203612doi  a(DE-B1597)648829  a(OCoLC)1419790021  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aREL0400002bisacsh1 aBoyarin, Daniel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRadical Jew :bPaul and the Politics of Identity /cDaniel Boyarin; ed. by Daniel Boyarin. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1994] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (400 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aContraversions: Critical Studies in Jewish Literature, Culture, and Society00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Wrestling with Paul -- t1 Circumcision, Allegory, and Universal "Man" -- t2 What Was Wrong with Judaism? The Cultural Politics of Pauline Scholarship -- t3 The Spirit and the Flesh" Paul's Political Anthropology -- t4 Moses' Veil; or, The Jewish Letter, the Christian Spirit -- t5 Circumcision and Revelation; or, The Politics of the Spirit -- t6 Was Paul an "Anti-Semite"? -- t7 Brides of Christ: Jeudshness and the Pauline Origins of Christian Sexual Renunciation -- t8 "There Is No Male and Female" Galatians and Gender Trouble -- t9 Paul, the "jewish Problem," and the "Woman Question" -- t10 Answering the Mail: Toward a Radical Jewishness -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDaniel Boyarin turns to the Epistles of Paul as the spiritual autobiography of a first-century Jewish cultural critic. What led Paul—in his dramatic conversion to Christianity—to such a radical critique of Jewish culture?Paul's famous formulation, "There is neither Jew nor Greek, no male and female in Christ," demonstrates the genius of Christianity: its concern for all people. The genius of Judaism is its validation of genealogy and cultural, ethnic difference. But the evils of these two thought systems are the obverse of their geniuses: Christianity has threatened to coerce universality, while ethnic difference is one of the most troubled issues in modern history.Boyarin posits a "diaspora identity" as a way to negotiate the pitfalls inherent in either position. Jewishness disrupts categories of identity because it is not national, genealogical, or even religious, but all of these, in dialectical tension with one another. It is analogous with gender: gender identity makes us different in some ways but not in others.An exploration of these tensions in the Pauline corpus, argues Boyarin, will lead us to a richer appreciation of our own cultural quandaries as male and female, gay and straight, Jew and Palestinian—and as human beings.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aJudaism (Christian theology)xHistory of doctrinesxEarly church, ca. 30-600. 0aJudaism (Christian theology)xHistory of doctrinesyEarly church, ca. 30-600. 4aGeneral. 4aJudaism. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / General.2bisacsh1 aBoyarin, Daniel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052021214540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092036140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520920361423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520920361/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles